    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <p>Born in Big Rapids, Michigan in 1913, Reginald Sharkey served in World War II and as an aviator until 1964 when he began work with the Michigan Department of Conservation, now the Department of Natural Resources. He specialized in Petoskey-area fisheries. During the late-sixties, Sharkey became an environmental reporter and columnist for several papers in Northern Michigan, including the <title render="italic">Petoskey News-Review</title> and the <title render="italic">Charlevoix County Press.</title> In 1997, at the age of 83, he published <title render="italic">The Blue Meteor: The Tragic Story of the Passenger Pigeon</title> with the Little Traverse Historical Society.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <p>The Reginald Sharkey collection consists of three series: Conservation Career, Writing Career, and Visual Materials. The collection's strength lies in drafts of Sharkey's columns, photographs, and drawings related to wildlife and the environment in Northern Michigan in the 1970s and 1980s.</p>
    </scopecontent>
